This system of arrangement will, it is believed, greatly facilitate a reference to any part- icular circumstance or event which it may be desired at any time to bring before the mind, inasmuch as a name or a term is more readily discoverable in a Vocabulary, than in a mass of Notes.

The Vocabularies have been rewritten, on a plan mainly corresponding with that followed in “ White’s J unior Scholar's Latin-English Dictionary.’'

Whenever the origin of a word is traceable to a pure Latin source, the etymology is given at the beginning of the article immediately after the state- ment of the mode of inflection. Next to the etymo- logy, the etymologica] meaning of the word is sup- plied. This is printed in Roman characters, within inverted commas, and placed within brackets, in order to distinguish it from the English renderings or equivalents, for which Italic type is employed.
